  "opinion": "As a mechanic in Milan who's seen the world through the lens of hands-on work and the quiet hum of engines, I've always believed that science isn't just about labs and equations—it's about understanding how things work, both the big and small. The gender gap in science, to me, isn't a single line on a chart but a series of invisible barriers that make it harder for some people to step into the field. I've met many women who've tried to pursue engineering or physics but got stopped by the idea that 'science is for boys'—a notion that's been around long enough to feel like it's part of the air we breathe. But it's not just about stereotypes; it's about the practical realities of being a woman in a male-dominated world. When I was growing up, my father, who had only upper secondary education, taught me to fix cars, and he always said, 'If you can do it with your hands, you can do it with your mind.' That's the spirit I hope to see in science: a place where everyone's hands and minds are valued equally. Should we address it? Absolutely. Not with grand gestures or top-down policies, but by creating spaces where people can learn without judgment. For example, in my shop, I've started a small workshop where women and men can work together on projects—no grades, no pressure, just building things. It's not about changing the system overnight, but about showing that science is for everyone, regardless of gender. How? By starting small, with conversations and community projects that let people see themselves in the work they do. The key isn't to fix the gap but to make it so that no one feels left out. After all, the best science comes from curiosity and collaboration, not from who you are or what you're told you're 'meant' to be.",
